Ever since Elon Musk launched his slash-and-burn effort to shrink the
federal government under the auspices of DOGE and with the blessing of Dona=
ld Trump, polls have demonstrated that voters are queasy about the idea. Th=
e latest survey from our partners at Echelon Insights found that a majority=
 of likely voters (51 percent) disapproved of Musk=E2=80=99s current role i=
n the federal government. And 57 percent said Musk was wrong to dismantle g=
overnment programs =E2=80=9Cwhen he wasn=E2=80=99t elected and has no exper=
tise in government.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

But despite the abundance of public polling about the administration since =
Trump took office just over a month ago, we haven=E2=80=99t seen many focus=
 groups, which lend useful texture that polls don=E2=80=99t capture. Polls,=
 for instance, don=E2=80=99t tell you that Musk is a =E2=80=9Cweird nerd,=
=E2=80=9D which is how Adam, a Trump-voting hockey fan from Macomb County, =
described the billionaire last week. Or that he=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Ccomple=
te tool,=E2=80=9D as
Michael from Milwaukee put it, or =E2=80=9Cscary=E2=80=9D (Tyesha in Toledo=
), or =E2=80=9Cselfish=E2=80=9D (DeAndre, also from Milwaukee) and just loo=
king to enrich himself. Perhaps Eric, a real estate appraiser from Pittsbur=
gh, put it most poignantly: =E2=80=9CExtremely radical. Scary. I just shudd=
er that Trump has given him carte blanche.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

These quotes are just a sample of
what swing voters in Michigan, Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Ohio, and Florida h=
ad to say about Musk during a series of mid-February focus groups commissio=
ned by Unite the Country, a Democratic super PAC formed in 2020 by a group =
of former Joe Biden aides to support his presidential bid. (The PAC shifted=
 its support to Kamala Harris last year.) After last year=E2=80=99s loss, I=
=E2=80=99ve had a running conversation with one of the group=E2=80=99s foun=
ders, the Florida-based strategist
Steve Schale, about how the Democratic Party=E2=80=99s brand has collapsed =
in recent years. =E2=80=9CThere is an urgent need for non-Beltway Democrati=
c strategists to help reshape the party=E2=80=99s narrative and revitalize =
its brand beyond Washington,=E2=80=9D said Schale, who helped engineer Bara=
ck Obama=E2=80=99s two Florida victories in 2008 and 2012. Over the weekend=
, Schale sent me the files from four focus groups commissioned by UTC and c=
onducted by the Democratic research firm Greenberg
Quinlan Rosner.

=C2=A0

Registered voters from the aforementioned states were divided into four buc=
kets: non-college voters of color who didn=E2=80=99t vote in 2024; white su=
burban swing voters who broke for Harris; non-college white voters under 50=
 in Macomb County who voted for Biden but flipped to Trump in 2024; and whi=
te men from Macomb County who voted for Trump but who are pro-choice. =E2=
=80=9CWe need to understand what has
happened to voters who either once voted for us, or were open to voting for=
 us,=E2=80=9D Schale told me. The Macomb focus groups conducted last week, =
he said, were the most instructive. =E2=80=9CMacomb County is a place that =
President Obama won by four points just 12 years ago, but by 2024, Trump wo=
n it by 12. Understanding what happened there is critical to clawing back a=
 few of those voters.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Focus groups are
hardly scientific, but they do provide valuable mood music=C2=A0 from the s=
tates that decide the presidency and control of Congress. A few big themes =
emerged from all four sessions: Musk and DOGE are viewed with deep skeptici=
sm, but Trump himself is seen as a man of action, especially compared to Bi=
den and the Democrats=E2=80=94a party described as =E2=80=9Cweak,=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9Cfeckless,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ctoo woke,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cout of=
 touch.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile, almost everyone in the groups said they primari=
ly get their news from social media, podcasts,
or local news stations. A few said they watched Fox News, but most said the=
y didn=E2=80=99t pay attention to traditional news organizations=E2=80=94TV=
 or digital. (Notably, several voters defined =E2=80=9Cheadlines=E2=80=9D a=
s the titles of YouTube videos.)

=C2=A0

Views on Trump were mixed, but voters were in agreement that he is stronger=
 and a more effective communicator than Biden, Harris, or anyone in the Dem=
ocratic Party. Many said they were giving the new
president the benefit of the doubt, as long as he could solve the problem t=
hat dominates conversations among their friends and family, the issue above=
 all other issues: the cost of living.

It=E2=80=99s the Economy, Stupid
--------------------------

Immigration, Ukraine, DOGE. In each focus group, the voters said they cared=
 about
Trump=E2=80=99s approach to all three issues, but across all races, genders=
, and political persuasions, those concerns were mostly just background noi=
se compared to the scourge of stubbornly high prices. =E2=80=9CMoney just d=
oesn=E2=80=99t go as far as it used to,=E2=80=9D said Chris, a Trump voter =
from Bloomfield Hills, Michigan. =E2=80=9CA hundred dollars used to last me=
 maybe five days. Now it doesn=E2=80=99t even last me half a second.=E2=80=
=9D

=C2=A0

The issue of rising costs has not gone away since last November, when it wa=
s the dominant theme of the election (at least until Harris made a final ca=
mpaign push about saving democracy). Almost every focus group voter complai=
ned about the cost of housing, eggs, bacon, gas, construction materials, in=
terest rates, you name it. Above all else, they said they want Trump to foc=
us on their pocketbooks and stop inflation for good. =E2=80=9CI think five =
years from now, if I could wake up and see a land of
opportunity again, like the America of old, and see people my age getting m=
ortgages without dual incomes, with decreasing costs, that would be a huge =
improvement,=E2=80=9D said Rob, a Latino entrepreneur from Tampa.

=C2=A0

As for the possibility that Trump=E2=80=99s tariffs will drive up prices? H=
is supporters in the Michigan focus groups had mixed opinions. =E2=80=9CI a=
m concerned about tariffs because we eat, sleep,
and breathe the automotive industry here,=E2=80=9D said Athena, a remote te=
ch worker who voted for Trump. =E2=80=9CIf they negatively impact the autom=
otive industry, to where they lay people off or they don=E2=80=99t produce =
as many cars, this area here will be very impacted. So will every other bus=
iness.=E2=80=9D Kelly, an education worker in Macomb County, said tariffs a=
re long overdue. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99ve been unfavorable to us for a real=
ly long time, so I think it=E2=80=99s totally fair that it goes back,=E2=80=
=9D
she said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not our job to take care of everybody else.=
=E2=80=9D

Most of the Trump voters in Michigan were willing to wait and see whether t=
he president=E2=80=99s policies would bring down costs. The Black and Latin=
o nonvoters were skeptical that the government could do anything to make th=
eir lives easier, while the Harris voters said tariffs will make costs high=
er. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m just hoping for the least damage possible,=E2=80=
=9D said Deborah, a retiree in Wisconsin who voted
for Harris.

Trump:
Action Hero
-----------

A major theme coursing through all the conversations was the idea of Trump=
=E2=80=99s strength,
or at least projection of strength. Trump=E2=80=99s flood-the-zone strategy=
=E2=80=94executive actions by the hour, filling screens large and small wit=
h a constant barrage of news=E2=80=94seems to be having the desired effect.=
 =E2=80=9CYou can see a difference between how other administrations were n=
ot doing any work, and how he is every day,=E2=80=9D said Kelly. =E2=80=9CH=
e=E2=80=99s attending events, meeting dignitaries, welcoming them to the co=
untry. He=E2=80=99s taking phone calls, he=E2=80=99s doing executive orders=
=2E He=E2=80=99s still got time for his
grandkids. It=E2=80=99s like the light is on in the White House at five in =
the morning.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Matt, another Trump voter from Macomb, echoed the point. =E2=80=9CIt proves=
 that they had the power to do things like that and just never did.=E2=80=
=9D Matt, sounding like every Trump voter ever, said he respected Trump=E2=
=80=99s willingness to take a billy club to Washington, but that he didn=E2=
=80=99t like his personal style: =E2=80=9CHe could
catch more bees with honey. He could do everything he=E2=80=99s doing in th=
e exact same way he=E2=80=99s doing it, and just not say dickhead things al=
l the time.=E2=80=9D

In every focus group, participants (even the Harris voters) said Trump=E2=
=80=99s always-on visibility made for a stark contrast to Biden. =E2=80=9CI=
t=E2=80=99s cruel that they made him be president and the guy was clearly m=
entally declining,=E2=80=9D said Andrew, a college professor from Columbus =
who voted for Harris. Asked to describe
Biden in one word, Eric, the Pittsburgh real estate appraiser who had no ki=
nd words for Musk, answered, =E2=80=9CWeak.=E2=80=9D He said Biden=E2=80=99=
s decision to run for a second term =E2=80=9Cwas such a joke, and he was cl=
early not fit to be president for the next four years.=E2=80=9D DeAndre fro=
m Milwaukee, one of the fence-sitting voters of color, was blunt in his des=
cription of Biden: =E2=80=9CBad. Old. Terrible.=E2=80=9D Rob, the Latino en=
trepreneur from Tampa, said it was silly that Democrats pretended Biden was=
 up for the job of a second
term, when it was plain to see that he was not. =E2=80=9CHe was doing old t=
hings like falling and appearing confused. I don=E2=80=99t agree with Trump=
, but he has the perception of strength.=E2=80=9D

Democrats Are Down Bad
----------------------

If Unite the Country were looking for proof that Democrats are in desperate=
 need of a
cause, leader, brand, issue set, anything=E2=80=A6 well, they found it. The=
 Trump voters, Harris voters, and nonvoters all failed to come up with some=
thing positive to say about the party. In the Michigan groups, the moderato=
r asked voters to succinctly describe the Republican Party. Words and phras=
es that came up: =E2=80=9Cpatriotic,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cstrong,=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9Cbuilding,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cunited.=E2=80=9D Asked to play word assoc=
iation about the Democrats, the voters offered =E2=80=9Cweak,=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9Cout of touch,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwoke.=E2=80=9D

Yes, most of the Michigan
participants voted for Trump, but those same voters said they=E2=80=99d vot=
ed for Democratic candidates in the past, and almost all said they fondly r=
emembered when Democrats put the focus squarely on working people rather th=
