x;">Ever since<strong> Elon Musk</strong> launched his slash-and-burn effor=
t to shrink the
federal government under the auspices of DOGE and with the blessing of <str=
ong>Donald Trump</strong>, polls have demonstrated that voters are queasy a=
bout the idea. The latest survey from our partners at Echelon Insights foun=
d that a majority of likely voters (51 percent) disapproved of Musk=E2=80=
=99s current role in the federal government. And 57 percent said Musk was w=
rong to dismantle government programs =E2=80=9Cwhen he wasn=E2=80=99t elect=
ed and has no expertise in government.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But despite the ab=
undance of public polling about the administration since Trump took office =
just over a month ago, we haven=E2=80=99t seen many <em>focus groups</em>, =
which lend useful texture that polls don=E2=80=99t capture. Polls, for inst=
ance, don=E2=80=99t tell you that Musk is a =E2=80=9Cweird nerd,=E2=80=9D w=
hich is how <strong>Adam</strong>, a Trump-voting hockey fan from Macomb Co=
unty, described the billionaire last week. Or that he=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9C=
complete tool,=E2=80=9D as
<strong>Michael</strong> from Milwaukee put it, or =E2=80=9Cscary=E2=80=9D =
(<strong>Tyesha</strong> in Toledo), or =E2=80=9Cselfish=E2=80=9D (<strong>=
DeAndre</strong>, also from Milwaukee) and just looking to enrich himself. =
Perhaps <strong>Eric</strong>, a real estate appraiser from Pittsburgh, put=
 it most poignantly: =E2=80=9CExtremely radical. Scary. I just shudder that=
 Trump has given him carte blanche.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">These quot=
es are just a sample of
what swing voters in Michigan, Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Ohio, and Florida h=
ad to say about Musk during a series of mid-February focus groups commissio=
ned by Unite the Country, a Democratic super PAC formed in 2020 by a group =
of former <strong>Joe Biden</strong> aides to support his presidential bid.=
 (The PAC shifted its support to <strong>Kamala Harris</strong> last year.)=
 After last year=E2=80=99s loss, I=E2=80=99ve had a running conversation wi=
th one of the group=E2=80=99s founders, the Florida-based strategist
<strong>Steve Schale</strong>, about how the Democratic Party=E2=80=99s bra=
nd has collapsed in recent years. =E2=80=9CThere is an urgent need for non-=
Beltway Democratic strategists to help reshape the party=E2=80=99s narrativ=
e and revitalize its brand beyond Washington,=E2=80=9D said Schale, who hel=
ped engineer <strong>Barack Obama</strong>=E2=80=99s two Florida victories =
in 2008 and 2012. Over the weekend, Schale sent me the files from four focu=
s groups commissioned by UTC and conducted by the Democratic research firm =
Greenberg
Quinlan Rosner.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Registered voters from the aforemention=
ed states were divided into four buckets: non-college voters of color who d=
idn=E2=80=99t vote in 2024; white suburban swing voters who broke for Harri=
s; non-college white voters under 50 in Macomb County who voted for Biden b=
ut flipped to Trump in 2024; and white men from Macomb County who voted for=
 Trump but who are pro-choice. =E2=80=9CWe need to understand what has
happened to voters who either once voted for us, or were open to voting for=
 us,=E2=80=9D Schale told me. The Macomb focus groups conducted last week, =
he said, were the most instructive. =E2=80=9CMacomb County is a place that =
President Obama won by four points just 12 years ago, but by 2024, Trump wo=
n it by 12. Understanding what happened there is critical to clawing back a=
 few of those voters.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Focus groups are
hardly scientific, but they do provide valuable mood music=C2=A0 from the s=
tates that decide the presidency and control of Congress. A few big themes =
emerged from all four sessions: Musk and DOGE are viewed with deep skeptici=
sm, but Trump himself is seen as a man of action, especially compared to Bi=
den and the Democrats=E2=80=94a party described as =E2=80=9Cweak,=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9Cfeckless,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ctoo woke,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cout of=
 touch.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile, almost everyone in the groups said they primari=
ly get their news from social media, podcasts,
or local news stations. A few said they watched Fox News, but most said the=
y didn=E2=80=99t pay attention to traditional news organizations=E2=80=94TV=
 or digital. (Notably, several voters defined =E2=80=9Cheadlines=E2=80=9D a=
s the titles of YouTube videos.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Views on Trump were mixed, but voters we=
re in agreement that he is stronger and a more effective communicator than =
Biden, Harris, or anyone in the Democratic Party. Many said they were givin=
g the new
president the benefit of the doubt, as long as he could solve the problem t=
hat dominates conversations among their friends and family, the issue above=
 all other issues: the cost of living.</p></div>
